art focus lecture impressionism and the american experience arts at stanford university presented by sica home search this site arts enews subscribe calendar art focus lecture impressionism and the american experience thursday march 1 2012 4 15pm cantor arts center auditorium cantor arts center member $75 non member $90 drop in attendance is offered for $30 on the day of a lecture if space is available no advance reservations are possible for drop in payment by check or cash accepted at the door thursdays march 1 8 and 15 denise erickson professor of art history at canada college and well known local lecturer returns to discuss impressionism and its effect on americans and their thirst for art when young american artists embarked on the greater journey to paris in the second half of the 19th century they discovered in the city of light a new style of painting dubbed impressionism inspired by the brilliance of the french masters american painters like john singer sargent william merritt chase childe hassam frank benson maurice prendergast and others found an audience both in europe and america that embraced the merger of the american experience with avant garde french art roots of american impressionism americans in paris and giverny early masters and collectors the growth of impressionism in america en plein air the ten and the legacy of american impressionism sponsored by cantor arts center click for more information home calendar gallery news visiting artists grants organizations facilities plan a visit about sica students faculty staff make a gift volunteer login press sitemap contact connect twitter facebook vimeo flickr 2011 stanford university all rights reserved local user login
